Our X-Shooter observations include several detections of the absorbing-galaxies. We detail our findings for each individual objects in turn below. Table~\ref{t:results_XSH} summarises the results.

 \vspace{0.3cm}
{\bf SDSS J002133.27+004300.9:} In the section above, we reported detection of {H$\alpha$}\ at the expected position of the absorbing-galaxy in this field. The X-Shooter observations confirm this detection. The {H$\alpha$}\ line is clearly seen in each 2D frame from individual OBs. The detections are even stronger in the most recent observations (taken in July 2015) notwithstanding that the requested constraints on the observing conditions are similar. An excerpt 2D frame is shown in the top panel of Fig~\ref{f:Q0021_EmLines_XSH}. The feature is clearly extended along the dispersion axis. The bottom panel of Fig~\ref{f:Q0021_EmLines_XSH} shows the 1D extracted spectrum together with a sky spectrum (red dotted line). We measure a H-$\alpha$ flux of F({H$\alpha$})=1.76$\times$10$^{-16}$ erg/s/cm$^2$, almost identical to our measurement from SINFONI observations (see Table~\ref{t:results_SINFO}). The agreement between the two measurements is remarkable given the uncertainties in flux calibration inherent to the X-Shooter instrument. 

There are strong hints of the presence of the {[N~{\sc ii}]}\ $\lambda$ 6585.27 emission line too (see Fig~\ref{f:Q0021_EmLines_XSH}). However, we notice the presence of an OH sky line at this wavelength. For this reason, we conservatively report a limit on the {[N~{\sc ii}]}\ flux of F({[N~{\sc ii}]})$<$1.7$\times$10$^{-18}$ erg/s/cm$^2$. Similarly, we report $<$1.1$\times$10$^{-18}$ erg/s/cm$^2$ from the non-detection of the {[N~{\sc ii}]}\ $\lambda$ 6549.86 in the X-Shooter NIR arm. In the VIS arm, the non-detection of both {[O~{\sc iii}]}\ and {[O~{\sc ii}]}\ doublets results in the following flux limits: F({[O~{\sc iii}]}\ $\lambda$ 5008)$<$0.7$\times$10$^{-18}$, F({[O~{\sc iii}]}\ $\lambda$ 4960)$<$0.7$\times$10$^{-18}$, F({[O~{\sc ii}]}\ $\lambda$ 7243)$<$0.8$\times$10$^{-18}$ and F({[O~{\sc ii}]}\ $\lambda$ 7237)$<$0.8$\times$10$^{-18}$ erg/s/cm$^2$.

